out and did
their thing and we did out
things.

11:10.003 --> 11:14.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We coordinated to some extent,
but it was
up to each individual member in
terms of how

11:14.641 --> 11:16.376 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they were going to handle it.

11:16.409 --> 11:19.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: But, Mr. Bennett,
with all these
Republicans, with so many
Republicans over

11:19.479 --> 11:24.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the weekend who -- many of them
in tough races,
many of them running for
reelection, saying

11:24.551 --> 11:29.222 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
that they are no longer
supporting Donald
Trump, is that the smart move?

11:29.255 --> 11:33.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARRY BENNETT, Former Trump
Campaign Senior
Adviser: Well, the smart move is
to recognize

11:33.526 --> 11:37.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the issues that he's
talking about and
how people are reacting to them
and talk about

11:37.297 --> 11:39.165 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
those issues.

11:39.198 --> 11:43.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, if this were an
election on personality,
Donald Trump would be down by
100 points.

11:43.469 --> 11:49.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, Hillary has spent $200
million pointing
out his perfectly obvious
imperfections.

11:49.175 --> 11:52.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the issues that he talks
about are why
people rally around him.

11:52.545 --> 11:55.448 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think it would be smart
for all candidates
to think about those issues.

11:55.481 --> 11:57.550 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: We have had -- let's
stay with
you.

11:57.584 --> 12:02.455 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We have had Donald Trump
tweeting out that
maybe Paul Ryan should be
focusing on balancing

12:02.488 --> 12:07.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the budget, creating jobs and
immigration
and not fighting with him, that
Kellyanne

12:07.460 --> 12:15.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Conway this morning talked about
inappropriate
behavior by some of the
Republicans who are

12:15.368 --> 12:17.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
now turning against him.

12:17.870 --> 12:21.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are we lining up with this sort
of one wing
of the party vs. another wing of
the party?

12:21.874 --> 12:23.343 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BARRY BENNETT: I hope not.

12:23.376 --> 12:25.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I hope we're lining up with
people who are
in real pain across America.

12:25.445 --> 12:26.746 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's what we should be talking
about.

12:26.779 --> 12:28.448 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's all Mr. Trump should be
talking about.

12:28.481 --> 12:31.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are people out there that
haven't had
a real increase in real wages in
a really

12:31.584 --> 12:32.785 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
long time.

12:32.819 --> 12:33.987 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's what he should be talking
about.

12:34.020 --> 12:35.455 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't care what Paul Ryan
does.

12:35.488 --> 12:39.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Paul Ryan's duty, as Tom's was,
is to help
elect members to the House.

12:39.192 --> 12:41.094 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Tom was very good at it.

12:41.127 --> 12:43.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Speaker Ryan needs to raise
a lot of money
to those done.

12:43.262 --> 12:45.231 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But they don't need to be
talking about each
other.

12:45.264 --> 12:47.033 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

12:47.066 --> 12:49.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM DAVIS: John, I don't think
there is any
question, though, that the Trump
constituency

12:49.702 --> 12:53.640 align:left position:0%,start line:66.67% size:100%
that came in, to some extent,
was anti-establishment,
and that means
anti-congressional
establishment.

12:53.673 --> 12:55.508 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There is some tension there.

12:55.541 --> 13:00.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question is, can they
coexist and get
along and maximize both their
outputs to produce

13:00.446 --> 13:04.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a Republican Congress and
perhaps elect a
Republican president?

13:04.450 --> 13:05.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, of course, there are
tensions there.

13:05.918 --> 13:07.553 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: What is the answer to
that question?

13:07.587 --> 13:09.155 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Can they get along and how can
they get along?

13:09.188 --> 13:10.256 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

13:10.289 --> 13:12.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TOM DAVIS: Well, I think members
-- it just
depends.

13:12.225 --> 13:14.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In some districts, you have
members endorsing
Trump, running with Trump,
coming to his Trump

13:15.028 --> 13:16.796 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
rallies.

13:16.829 --> 13:19.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In other districts, you won't be
able to find
them with a search if Trump
comes to town.

13:19.065 --> 13:20.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It really depends.

13:20.166 --> 13:22.035 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we have always had to run
our own races.

13:22.068 --> 13:26.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have found, in my district out
here in Northern
Virginia, after a couple of
terms, there were

13:26.139 --> 13:30.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very few Republicans I could
really appear
with without hurting myself.

13:30.543 --> 13:34.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You were trying to be a team
player, but,
first of all, you owe yourself
and the caucus

13:34.414 --> 13:36.182 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a duty to get reelected.

13:36.215 --> 13:39.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Donald Trump performs very
well in some
districts, and in some
districts, he's not.

13:39.752 --> 13:43.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Mr. Bennett, over the
weekend,
we saw Paul Ryan actually get
booed when he

13:43.923 --> 13:52.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
talked about the situation, the
videotape,
and that Trump wasn't with him,
as he was

13:52.532 --> 13:54.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
scheduled to be.

13:54.333 --> 14:00.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When Joe Heck in Nevada, a
Senate candidate,
withdrew his endorsement of Mr.
Trump, he

14:00.273 --> 14:01.674 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
got booed.

14:01.708 --> 14:06.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is there a risk for candidates
who are jumping
off the Trump bandwagon?

14:06.913 --> 14:08.548 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BARRY BENNETT: Yes.

14:08.581 --> 14:12.118 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I mean, no one's ever
successfully sawed a
boat in half and floated to
safety.

14:12.151 --> 14:15.388 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Once we're in the boat, we're in
the boat.

14:15.421 --> 14:19.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We need the presidential race --
if not it's
winnable, we need it to be very
close in order

14:19.358 --> 14:23.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for those House and Senate races
like Joe
Heck to get across the line.

14:23.129 --> 14:25.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, you have got to be very
careful.

14:25.331 --> 14:30.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can have your own opinions,
but realize
that 40 or 50 or 60 percent of
your supporters

14:30.870 --> 14:31.838 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
are still with him.

14:31.871 --> 14:33.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So don't go too far.

14:33.840 --> 14:39.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Mr. Davis, if you
were running
the Congressional Campaign
Committee now,

14:39.579 --> 14:43.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what would you be telling
challengers, what
would be your members who are
running for

14:43.816 --> 14:44.784 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
reelection?

14:44.817 --> 14:45.785 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

14:45.818 --> 14:46.786 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TOM DAVIS: Well, it's district
by district.

14:46.819 --> 14:48.521 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I think you look at the top
of the ticket.

14:48.554 --> 14:51.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If it helps you, you want to try
to latch
onto those coattails and ride
across the line.

14:51.457 --> 14:55.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If the wind is coming at you,
you are going
to have to basically personalize
the district,

14:55.361 --> 14:57.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
carve your own identity, make
this a referendum
on you.

14:57.897 --> 15:00.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
By the way, the NRCC has been
pretty successful.

15:00.666 --> 15:05.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
John Katko's district up in
Syracuse, he's
running double digits ahead, and
Mr. Trump

15:05.271 --> 15:07.340 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is running double digits behind.

15:07.373 --> 15:09.776 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Everybody understands this.

15:09.809 --> 15:13.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Professionals understand you do
what you have
to do to get reelected at this
point.

15:13.546 --> 15:17.450 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mr. Trump's remarks, nobody's
going to attach
themselves to those remarks.

15:17.483 --> 15:19.418 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You won't find anybody coming
forward.

15:19.452 --> 15:23.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But that doesn't necessarily
mean you abandon
ship, because, once you divide
yourself up,

15:23.322 --> 15:26.692 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have seen very few cases where
parties survive
that kind of thing.

15:26.726 --> 15:32.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Mr. Bennett, no
matter what happens
at the top of the ticket in
November, this

15:32.498 --> 15:36.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
anti-establishment feeling that
you have been
talking about is going to be
there.

15:36.669 --> 15:38.905 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's going to continue and it's
going to exist.

15:38.938 --> 15:42.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What does the Republican Party
look like moving
forward?

15:42.608 --> 15:44.577 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What does it do moving forward,
win or lose?

15:44.610 --> 15:50.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because even if Donald Trump is
elected president,
he will have to deal with this
Congress that

15:50.349 --> 15:55.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is the establishment that so
many of his supporters
hate right now.

15:55.354 --> 15:59.058 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARRY BENNETT: Well, I think the
Freedom Caucus
probably gets larger.

15:59.091 --> 16:01.093 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think that there's going to be
more turmoil.

16:01.127 --> 16:06.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think that if we think the
scary stuff
is over now, wait until after
the election,

16:06.399 --> 16:10.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because the winner is probably
only going
to get 46, 47 percent of the
vote, so more

16:10.837 --> 16:13.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people will have not voted for
them than voted
for them.

16:13.673 --> 16:17.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the next four years in
Washington, I don't
predict calm seas.

16:17.310 --> 16:22.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: What would you do,
Mr. Davis, if
you were running a party and, if
you were

16:22.481 --> 16:24.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the RNC chairman?

16:24.250 --> 16:26.619 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How would you move forward after
the election,
no matter who wins?

16:26.652 --> 16:27.887 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

16:27.920 --> 16:29.655 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TOM DAVIS: Well, look, we have
got to learn
how to coexist.

16:29.689 --> 16:32.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What the Republicans have found
in my state
of Virginia is, even when
they're united,

16:32.892 --> 16:35.294 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
given the Democratic shifts, we
lose sometimes.

16:35.328 --> 16:38.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you are going to have to
learn to coexist,
everybody get a piece of things
and try to

16:38.798 --> 16:40.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
line up accordingly.

16:40.566 --> 16:42.468 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're going to primaries,
instead of conventions.

16:42.501 --> 16:44.270 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think that's a good thing in
this state.

16:44.303 --> 16:48.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it shouldn't jeopardize the
Trump supporters
either, who won primaries.

16:48.941 --> 16:51.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's the kind of thing where
we are going
to have to learn to coexist.

16:51.644 --> 16:53.479 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Politics is parties are
coalitions.

16:53.512 --> 16:56.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And coalitions mean sometimes
you get in a
room with people you're not
quite comfortable

16:56.916 --> 16:58.818 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with to advance your own
interests.

16:58.851 --> 17:02.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the Republicans have not
gotten comfortable
with their coalition.

17:02.255 --> 17:06.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Democrats, which are also a
diverse coalition,
have learned to coexist and win.

17:06.058 --> 17:09.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Tom Davis, Barry
Bennett, thanks
so much for coming in and
discussing these

17:10.029 --> 17:11.130 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
interesting days with us.

17:11.163 --> 17:12.131 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

17:12.164 --> 17:13.132 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
TOM DAVIS: Thank you.

17:13.165 --> 17:15.001 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BARRY BENNETT: Thanks.

17:15.034 --> 17:17.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That brings us
to our Politics
Monday duo, Amy Walter of The
Cook Political

17:17.904 --> 17:21.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Report and Tamara Keith of NPR,
joining us
tonight from Detroit.

17:21.407 --> 17:27.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Amy, let's start with this
evaporation
of support from some Republican
leadership.

17:27.046 --> 17:28.414 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Does it matter?

17:28.447 --> 17:30.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMY WALTER, The Cook Political
Report: Oh,
it absolutely matters.

17:30.216 --> 17:35.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you think back to the 2012
election, Mitt
Romney, of course, lost the
campaign.

17:35.388 --> 17:39.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He lost while getting 93 percent
of the Republican
vote.

17:39.325 --> 17:44.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Getting less than 90 percent is
a big problem
in a country that is as
polarized as this.

17:44.864 --> 17:49.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so even if it's only 5 or 10
percent of
voters, not necessarily who even
just go out

17:49.468 --> 17:54.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and vote for Hillary Clinton,
but the bigger
concern, I think, for
Republicans down ballot

17:54.240 --> 17:57.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is that traditional Republican
voters stay
home.

17:57.510 --> 18:00.746 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They find themselves so
disgusted by this
race, they can't support Donald
Trump, they

18:00.780 --> 18:05.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
don't like Hillary Clinton, and
so they sit
on their hands, they don't turn
out.

18:05.551 --> 18:10.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is a bigger problem, I
think, for down-ballot
races than almost anything else.

18:10.456 --> 18:14.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Tamara, what
does it mean
when the man, Paul Ryan, two
heartbeats away

18:14.226 --> 18:20.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from the president, the leader
of the House,
says that he's not necessarily
unendorsing

18:20.333 --> 18:22.635 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Donald Trump, but he's not
backing him, he's
not going to spend more effort?

18:22.668 --> 18:25.705 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH, National Public
Radio: He's
in absolutely a tough position.

18:25.738 --> 18:31.310 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And he's been in a tough
position, and really
the Trump candidacy has put a
ton of Republicans

